00:00:25.745 --> 00:00:27.370
DAVID THORBURN: There
are various kinds

00:00:27.370 --> 00:00:32.210
of neorealisms, flavors of
neorealism-- an Italian flavor,

00:00:32.210 --> 00:00:33.250
a French flavor.

00:00:33.250 --> 00:00:35.810
There is a kind of
tonal difference

00:00:35.810 --> 00:00:37.350
that's worth paying
attention to.

00:00:37.350 --> 00:00:41.010
And I maybe I can capture
it over-simply in two

00:00:41.010 --> 00:00:42.500
short clips for you.

00:00:42.500 --> 00:00:44.670
So the first clip
I want to show you

00:00:44.670 --> 00:00:48.950
is from an Italian neorealist
film, the last really

00:00:48.950 --> 00:00:53.360
powerful fully neorealist film
that De Sica himself directed,

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:56.740
a film called Umberto
D, made in 1952.

00:00:56.740 --> 00:00:57.406
