00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:17.140
Did you see how Umberto
looked at the man who

00:02:17.140 --> 00:02:19.120
sat down next to him?

00:02:19.120 --> 00:02:21.300
I think the purpose
of that close look

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:25.020
was to make the audience look at
him too, pay attention to him,

00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:26.400
even though he
never says a word.

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:33.565
It's possible that
these scenes might

00:02:33.565 --> 00:02:34.940
make some members
of the audience

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:37.190
think that he's thinking
about jumping off a building.

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:42.250
All right, freeze it, James.

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:43.600
Back it up two seconds.

00:02:43.600 --> 00:02:46.100
This is the last moment in the
scene that I want you to see.

00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:47.570
Look what happened here.

00:02:47.570 --> 00:02:48.822
Why are you smiling?

00:02:48.822 --> 00:02:49.950
AUDIENCE: It's because
he was facing--

00:02:49.950 --> 00:02:51.355
DAVID THORBURN: Speak
up so everyone can hear.

00:02:51.355 --> 00:02:52.854
AUDIENCE: It's
because he was facing

00:02:52.854 --> 00:02:54.430
towards the middle of the bus.

00:02:54.430 --> 00:02:56.197
And then, Umberto, he got up--

00:02:56.197 --> 00:02:56.780
[END PLAYBACK]

00:02:56.780 --> 00:02:58.190
--and he turned right forward.

00:02:58.190 --> 00:02:59.415
DAVID THORBURN: Yes, as
if he had more space.

00:02:59.415 --> 00:02:59.690
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:00.570
DAVID THORBURN:
But then what else?

00:03:00.570 --> 00:03:01.580
What about the gesture?

00:03:01.580 --> 00:03:02.950
What do we feel about this man?

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:04.080
Never says a word.

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:06.360
Sits down next to him Umberto.

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:08.970
When he goes like this,
what do we feel about him?

00:03:08.970 --> 00:03:11.630
He has some horrible story too.

00:03:11.630 --> 00:03:17.650
He maybe is in much
despair as Umberto.

00:03:17.650 --> 00:03:19.260
The point, of
course, is remember

00:03:19.260 --> 00:03:23.680
I talked quite a bit
in earlier lectures

00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:25.190
about what I called
the retarding

00:03:25.190 --> 00:03:28.880
impulse in certain
neorealist films

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:33.190
and also in certain films of
Renoir-- the extent to which

00:03:33.190 --> 00:03:36.920
what suddenly happens, as the
camera is looking at the world,

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:40.530
it finds a locus of
interest that may

00:03:40.530 --> 00:03:42.640
be distracting in some sense.

00:03:42.640 --> 00:03:44.840
Now it doesn't truly
distract in the sense

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:48.030
that it takes you off completely
on a digressive course.

00:03:48.030 --> 00:03:52.090
But what it reminds you of is
the complexity of the world.

00:03:52.090 --> 00:03:55.190
What it reminds you of--
this particular scene

00:03:55.190 --> 00:03:58.530
especially-- is there's plenty
of despair to go around.

00:03:58.530 --> 00:04:01.490
What it reminds you of is
that the story that has not

00:04:01.490 --> 00:04:05.080
been told about this man--
this silent, suffering,

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:08.600
working man who sat down next
to old Umberto-- probably

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:11.570
has a story, just as
poignant, just as terrible

00:04:11.570 --> 00:04:13.637
as Umberto himself.

00:04:13.637 --> 00:04:15.220
And it's one of the
ways that the film

00:04:15.220 --> 00:04:18.140
has of enlarging
the implications

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:21.320
of the individuated
story that it tells.

00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:25.380
But the most significant
thing about this moment--

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:29.490
so it's a moment in which the
camera doesn't actually swerve,

00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:34.020
but even though our hero, the
protagonist, moves off the bus,

00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:37.550
the camera stays briefly
on that man with the hat.

00:04:37.550 --> 00:04:40.980
Can we watch it-- just the very
end, James-- one more time,

00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:42.366
just to get another look at it?

00:04:42.366 --> 00:04:51.880
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:04:51.880 --> 00:04:53.610
See, that's a gesture
of, what, despair?

00:04:53.610 --> 00:04:54.193
[END PLAYBACK]

00:04:54.193 --> 00:04:55.100
Misery?

00:04:55.100 --> 00:04:55.990
Sadness?

00:04:55.990 --> 00:04:57.410
Sorrow?

00:04:57.410 --> 00:05:00.930
Reflection over what terrible
things are about to happen?

00:05:00.930 --> 00:05:04.050
And the idea that that
story has not been told

00:05:04.050 --> 00:05:06.870
is as significant for our
understanding of the film

00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:08.320
as the story that is told.

00:05:11.770 --> 00:05:13.720
So there's a
similar-- I don't want

00:05:13.720 --> 00:05:16.440
to call it a digressive
impulse, but let's call it

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:19.680
an impulse toward
noticing what is not

00:05:19.680 --> 00:05:20.825
at the center of the story.

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:26.620
We might call it an impulse
toward a partial kind

00:05:26.620 --> 00:05:31.920
of abstraction, an attentiveness
to the world that is always

00:05:31.920 --> 00:05:36.680
threatened or challenged
by new options

00:05:36.680 --> 00:05:38.260
that it might want to look at.

00:05:38.260 --> 00:05:43.690
And not all of these impulses
lead to misery or despair,

00:05:43.690 --> 00:05:46.010
even in the
neorealist tradition.

00:05:46.010 --> 00:05:47.750
But the point I want
to make is that I

00:05:47.750 --> 00:05:52.990
think the neorealist
tradition lays more emphasis

00:05:52.990 --> 00:05:54.310
on social problems.

00:05:54.310 --> 00:06:01.410
Its stories are often parables
of impoverishment or parables

00:06:01.410 --> 00:06:03.400
about disempowerment.

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:07.080
Now the film you're going to
see tonight, The 400 Blows,

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:09.650
could in many ways be said
to fit that description.

00:06:09.650 --> 00:06:14.760
But there's a lightness,
a lyricism in it,

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:20.630
that doesn't sustain the heavy
mood, the mood of disturbance,

00:06:20.630 --> 00:06:30.020
the mood of-- if not tragedy--
of misery, or at least

00:06:30.020 --> 00:06:33.340
of very alert social
awareness that

00:06:33.340 --> 00:06:35.159
permeates neorealist films.

00:06:35.159 --> 00:06:37.700
So here's a moment from the film
you're going to see tonight.

00:06:37.700 --> 00:06:39.840
But it's a very
distracting moment.

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:42.850
You won't forget
it, when you see it.

00:06:42.850 --> 00:06:45.626
And I'm doing a little harm
to your experience of the film

00:06:45.626 --> 00:06:47.500
by calling your attention
to it, because it's

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:50.960
such a strange
moment in the film.

00:06:50.960 --> 00:06:55.270
The hero is one of these two
boys, the boy on the left.

00:06:55.270 --> 00:06:59.090
And the guy on the
right-- if you're

00:06:59.090 --> 00:07:02.840
facing the film-- to your left
is the hero, the protagonist.

00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:04.810
And the boy on the right
is his best friend.

00:07:04.810 --> 00:07:07.560
The girl in the
middle is a sister.

00:07:07.560 --> 00:07:09.860
And they're accompanying
this girl-- this

00:07:09.860 --> 00:07:12.977
is in the middle of the film.

00:07:12.977 --> 00:07:15.310
We're not even told where
they're going when it happens,

00:07:15.310 --> 00:07:18.050
but they're going to the
park to watch a puppet show.

00:07:18.050 --> 00:07:21.840
And watch what happens.

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:23.720
We're in the middle of the film.

00:07:23.720 --> 00:07:25.370
We already know a
lot about the boys.

00:07:25.370 --> 00:07:28.966
The boys have played
hooky, neither of them

00:07:28.966 --> 00:07:30.591
get along very well
with their parents.

00:07:33.210 --> 00:07:33.876
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

